<!-- SECTION 3 — 30-DAY PLAN -->
<div id="plan" class="section">

  <div class="section-header">
    <div class="eyebrow">30-Day Plan</div>
    <h2>The Practice That Stays</h2>
    <p>Regulation is not built in a session. It is built in the days after, when the insight is fading and the pattern is returning. This plan is designed to be used — not just read. Tick each day as you complete it.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- WEEK 1 -->
  <div class="week-block">
    <div class="week-header">
      <h3>Week One — Notice</h3>
      <span class="week-theme">Days 1–7 · Finding the signal</span>
    </div>
    <div class="week-body">
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 1</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The morning pause</div>
          <div class="day-body">Before anything else — before the phone, before the email — sit for five minutes. No agenda. Just notice what is there. You are not trying to fix anything. You are learning to stop before the day takes over.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 2</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The body scan</div>
          <div class="day-body">Once today, before a significant task: close your eyes for 60 seconds. Head to feet. Where is the tension? Name it in one word. That noticing is neurologically active — it reduces intensity before you have done anything else.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 3</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">Name the signal</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, notice once when your archetype pattern activates — the doing that accelerates, the flatness that arrives, the analysis that builds, the yes that costs you. Just name it. That is the whole practice today.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 4</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The physiological sigh</div>
          <div class="day-body">Two inhales through the nose — the second one slightly longer, filling the lungs. One long exhale through the mouth. Three repetitions. 60 seconds. Use it before your most demanding moment today. Notice what changes.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 5</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The self-compassion question</div>
          <div class="day-body">When the inner critic fires today — after a mistake, a delay, an imperfect moment — ask: what would I say to someone I respect in exactly this situation? Say that to yourself. Not flattery. Honest kindness.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 6</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The somatic shake</div>
          <div class="day-body">Stand. Loose hands. Shake from the wrists upward — through the arms, the shoulders, the chest. 60 seconds. It looks slightly ridiculous. That is precisely the point — it dissolves the professional armour before anything else can land.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 7</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The first reflection</div>
          <div class="day-body">Read back through the week. What did you notice that you would not normally have noticed? What shifted, even slightly? What is the earliest signal you have found? That signal is your most important tool going forward.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- WEEK 2 -->
  <div class="week-block">
    <div class="week-header">
      <h3>Week Two — Interrupt</h3>
      <span class="week-theme">Days 8–14 · Catching the pattern before it runs</span>
    </div>
    <div class="week-body">
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 8</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The vortex breath — anchored</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, attach the vortex breath to an existing trigger — before a meeting, after lunch, at the end of the morning. The anchor is what makes the habit automatic. Choose the trigger once and use it all week.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 9</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The ten-second pause</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, once: when you notice the pattern activating, pause for ten seconds before acting on it. You do not have to change what you do. Just insert the pause. The pause is the practice.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 10</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The reframe question — used live</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, use your archetype's reframe question in the moment — not in reflection afterwards. When the signal arrives: pause, ask the question, name what comes. One word is enough. Then proceed.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 11</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">Rest — explicitly protected</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, put one block of genuine rest in the diary. Not productive rest. Not useful rest. Just rest — because the nervous system that does not rest cannot regulate well. Treat it as non-negotiable.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 12</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The mantra — out loud</div>
          <div class="day-body">Say your mantra out loud today — not silently, not as a thought. Out loud. Notice where in your body you feel it land. The right mantra will feel slightly uncomfortable — not because it is wrong, but because you have not believed it yet.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 13</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The body scan before a meeting</div>
          <div class="day-body">Before your most significant meeting today: 60-second body scan. Head to feet. Notice what you are carrying into the room. Name it. That noticing changes the quality of your presence before you have said a word.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 14</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The second reflection</div>
          <div class="day-body">Read back through week two. When did the interruption work? When did you miss it? What was the difference between those moments? That difference is where the next layer of the practice lives.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- WEEK 3 -->
  <div class="week-block">
    <div class="week-header">
      <h3>Week Three — Deepen</h3>
      <span class="week-theme">Days 15–21 · The practice becomes a pattern</span>
    </div>
    <div class="week-body">
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 15</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The end-of-day check-in</div>
          <div class="day-body">Every evening this week: what did I feel today that I did not name aloud? What did I need that I did not give myself? What am I proud of — however small? Three lines. That is the practice.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 16</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The full sequence — once</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, use the full sequence for your archetype: movement, then breath, then reframe. In that order. Notice whether doing them in sequence feels different to doing each one alone.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 17</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">Permission — practised</div>
          <div class="day-body">Say this out loud: I am allowed to slow down. I am allowed to take up space. I am allowed to need things. Notice the discomfort. Sit with it briefly. Let it pass. That passing is the practice.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 18</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The relational check</div>
          <div class="day-body">Think of one person in your professional life who experiences your dysregulated pattern most directly. You do not need to tell them. Just hold them in mind. Then ask: what would change for them if I caught the signal ten minutes earlier?</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 19</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">Something restorative — protected</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, protect time for something that restores you specifically — not a general idea of restoration, but the thing that actually works for you. Movement, stillness, connection, creativity. Whatever is yours. Protect it before the day fills.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 20</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The earliest signal — revisited</div>
          <div class="day-body">Return to the earliest signal you identified in week one. Has it changed? Are you noticing it earlier now? The shrinking of the gap between signal and noticing is the evidence that the practice is working.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 21</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The third reflection</div>
          <div class="day-body">Three weeks in. What has genuinely shifted — even slightly? What has the practice revealed about your pattern that you did not know at the start? Write one honest paragraph. That paragraph is your evidence.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- WEEK 4 -->
  <div class="week-block">
    <div class="week-header">
      <h3>Week Four — Sustain</h3>
      <span class="week-theme">Days 22–30 · Building what lasts</span>
    </div>
    <div class="week-body">
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 22</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The one practice that works</div>
          <div class="day-body">By now you know which practice has had the most impact. Today, name it specifically. Write it down. That is the one you are keeping — not because the others do not matter, but because one consistent practice is worth ten inconsistent ones.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 23</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The mantra — tested under pressure</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, notice a moment of pressure and use the mantra in it — not before or after, but in the middle of it. That is the real test of a mantra. It is not for calm moments. It is for this one.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 24</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The peer conversation</div>
          <div class="day-body">Regulation is relational. Today, have a conversation with one person from the session — or someone who understands what you are working on. Not to perform progress. To stay connected to the work. The conversation is part of the practice.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 25</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">Rest — without justification</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, rest without earning it first. Not because everything is done. Not as a reward. Just rest — because the regulated leader includes themselves in the care they give to everyone else.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 26</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The full sequence revisited</div>
          <div class="day-body">Movement, breath, reframe — the full sequence, used intentionally. Notice whether it feels different to day 16. The sequence should feel less effortful now. That ease is the practice becoming a pattern.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 27</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">What the people closest to you have noticed</div>
          <div class="day-body">Ask one person — a colleague, a partner, a trusted friend — if they have noticed anything different in you over the past four weeks. You do not need to explain what you have been doing. Just listen to what they say.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 28</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The next archetype edge</div>
          <div class="day-body">Every archetype has a next layer. The Navigator who can pause is now working on stillness. The Anchor who breathes is now working on asking for what they need. What is your next edge? Name it. That is your next thirty days.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 29</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The letter to yourself — revisited</div>
          <div class="day-body">Return to what you wrote in the exercise section of this playbook — particularly the last question: what you now know. Read it. Does it still hold? Has the knowing deepened? What would you add?</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
      <div class="day-row">
        <div class="day-num">DAY 30</div>
        <div class="day-content">
          <div class="day-title">The return</div>
          <div class="day-body">Today, revisit the scenario from the session — the one that asked you to pause. What do you notice now that you did not see before? What has changed in how you understand your own pattern? That change is the work. That change is the point.</div>
        </div>
        <input type="checkbox" class="day-check">
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

